<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="431" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1763,2042]" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1835,1861]" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The female of this species differs from the congeners occurring in the region by having indistinct epigynal fovea (
<emphasis box="[335,358,1872,1897]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">vs</emphasis>
. transverse or triangular) and a pair of longitudinal sclerotizations in the center of the epigynal plate (
<figureCitation box="[222,338,1907,1934]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1220,1244]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1181]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[151,1436,181,1196]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Epigynes of Trygetus nakhchivanicus sp. n. (A–C), T. gromovi Marusik, 2011 (D–F), T. susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021 (G–I) and T. Jacksoni Marusik &amp; Guseinov, 2003 (J). A, D, G vulva, dorsal; B, E, H, J intact epigyne, ventral; C, F macerated epigyne, ventral and antero-ventral; I right receptacle, dorsal. D–F after Marusik (2011), G–I after Zamani &amp; Marusik (2021) and J after Marusik &amp; Guseinov (2003). Scale bars: A–I = 0.2 mm (not provided for J). Abbreviations: Bu—bursa, Fo—fovea, Re—receptacle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683487" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683487/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">Fig. 6G–I</figureCitation>
). The male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zamani &amp; Marusik" authorityYear="2021" box="[504,629,1908,1933]" class="Arachnida" family="Zodariidae" genus="Trygetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="431" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="susianus">
<emphasis box="[504,629,1908,1933]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">T. susianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the congeners occurring in the Mediterranean by the nonfilamentous embolus (
<emphasis box="[403,426,1944,1969]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">vs</emphasis>
. filamentous in other species; cf. 
<figureCitation box="[809,909,1943,1969]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1975,1999]" captionTargetBox="[183,1395,466,1939]" captionTargetId="figure-108@11.[171,1417,453,1952]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male palp of Trygetus susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021. A ventroretrolateral; B prolateral; C dorsal; D, E anteroventral. Scale bar = 0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Co—conductor, Em—embolus, Ta—tegular apophysis, St—subtegulum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683501" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683501/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Levy, G." box="[964,1090,1943,1970]" pageId="8" pageNumber="431" pagination="67 - 110" refId="ref6399" refString="Levy, G. (1992) The spider genera Palaestina, Trygetus, Zodarion and Ranops (Araneae, Zodariidae) in Israel with annotations on species of the Middle East. Israel Journal of Zoology, 38, 67 - 110." type="journal article" year="1992">Levy 1992</bibRefCitation>
: figs 35, 43). It differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2022" authorityName="Zamani &amp; Marusik" authorityYear="2022" class="Arachnida" family="Zodariidae" genus="Trygetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="431" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nakhchivanicus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1414,1430,1944,1969]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,325,1979,2005]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">nakhchivanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[332,394,1979,2005]" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[332,394,1979,2005]" pageId="8" pageNumber="431" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, the most similar species, by the shape (i.e. not sharply pointed) and size of RTA (shorter than tibia 
<emphasis box="[208,231,2016,2041]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">vs</emphasis>
. longer), and the tegular apophysis lacking lobes (cf. 
<figureCitation box="[833,1009,2015,2041]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[314,1288,188,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-30@10.[265,1323,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 9. Male palps of Trygetus nakhchivanicus sp. n. (A–B) and T. susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021 (C–D). A, C retrolateral; B, D ventral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683499" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683499/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="431">Fig. 9D and 9B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="432" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,150,176]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[563,646,150,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1846,1870]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,348,1822]" captionTargetId="figure-87@6.[151,1436,345,1822]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Habitus of Trygetus gromovi Marusik, 2011 (A–D), T. susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021 (E), T. cyrus sp. n. (F) and T. nakhchivanicus sp. n. (G, H). A, F female, dorsal; B same, lateral; C female’s abdomen and posterior part of cephalothorax, ventral; D female’s cephalothorax, anterior; E, H male, dorsal; G same, ventral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm, unless stated otherwise." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683485" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683485/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
. Total length 1.85. Carapace 0.86 long, 0.58 wide. Eye sizes:AME: 0.08, ALE: 0.04, PLE: 0.04, vestigial PMEs seem present. Carapace, sternum, labium, chelicerae and maxillae yellowish; carapace with several rows of pores on pars thoracica. Legs yellowish, without annulations. Abdomen with dorsal and ventral scuta, dorsally pale beige, ventrally yellowish. Spinnerets pale, uniform in color. Measurements of Fe: I: 0.55, II: 0.50, III: 0.46, IV: 0.62, rest of the segments missing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">
Palp as in 
<figureCitation box="[315,438,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1982,2006]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,741,1959]" captionTargetId="figure-267@9.[170,1416,741,1959]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. SEM images of the male palp of Trygetus susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021. A distal; B–D ventral; E retrolateral. Scale bars: D, E = 0.1 mm (not provided for A–C). Abbreviations: Co—conductor, Rf—furrow of RTA." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683553" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683553/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Figs 8A–E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[450,520,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[314,1288,188,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-30@10.[265,1323,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 9. Male palps of Trygetus nakhchivanicus sp. n. (A–B) and T. susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021 (C–D). A, C retrolateral; B, D ventral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683499" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683499/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">9C–D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[531,614,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1975,1999]" captionTargetBox="[183,1395,466,1939]" captionTargetId="figure-108@11.[171,1417,453,1952]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male palp of Trygetus susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021. A ventroretrolateral; B prolateral; C dorsal; D, E anteroventral. Scale bar = 0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Co—conductor, Em—embolus, Ta—tegular apophysis, St—subtegulum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683501" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683501/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">10A–E</figureCitation>
; femur almost 3 times longer than wide, 1.2 times shorter than cymbium; patella as long as wide; tibia shorter than wide, RTA consisted of ventral and retrolateral parts divided by furrow (
<emphasis box="[1404,1429,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Rf</emphasis>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,237,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1982,2006]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,741,1959]" captionTargetId="figure-267@9.[170,1416,741,1959]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. SEM images of the male palp of Trygetus susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021. A distal; B–D ventral; E retrolateral. Scale bars: D, E = 0.1 mm (not provided for A–C). Abbreviations: Co—conductor, Rf—furrow of RTA." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683553" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683553/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Fig. 8E</figureCitation>
), ventral part rounded, retrolateral part diamond shaped; cymbium unmodified, 2 times longer than wide; bulb almost round, with distinct subtegulum (
<emphasis box="[658,680,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">St</emphasis>
), tegular apophysis (
<emphasis box="[914,941,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Ta</emphasis>
) hook-like, lacking distinct lobes, with deep groove (
<figureCitation box="[245,333,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1982,2006]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,741,1959]" captionTargetId="figure-267@9.[170,1416,741,1959]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. SEM images of the male palp of Trygetus susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021. A distal; B–D ventral; E retrolateral. Scale bars: D, E = 0.1 mm (not provided for A–C). Abbreviations: Co—conductor, Rf—furrow of RTA." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683553" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683553/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
); embolus (
<emphasis box="[466,503,475,500]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Em</emphasis>
) broad, originating at about 9 o’clock position, terminal part complex with several outgrowths (
<figureCitation box="[293,429,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1975,1999]" captionTargetBox="[183,1395,466,1939]" captionTargetId="figure-108@11.[171,1417,453,1952]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male palp of Trygetus susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021. A ventroretrolateral; B prolateral; C dorsal; D, E anteroventral. Scale bar = 0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Co—conductor, Em—embolus, Ta—tegular apophysis, St—subtegulum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683501" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683501/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Fig. 10A–E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">
Female. Epigyne as in 
<figureCitation box="[452,563,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1220,1244]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1181]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[151,1436,181,1196]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Epigynes of Trygetus nakhchivanicus sp. n. (A–C), T. gromovi Marusik, 2011 (D–F), T. susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021 (G–I) and T. Jacksoni Marusik &amp; Guseinov, 2003 (J). A, D, G vulva, dorsal; B, E, H, J intact epigyne, ventral; C, F macerated epigyne, ventral and antero-ventral; I right receptacle, dorsal. D–F after Marusik (2011), G–I after Zamani &amp; Marusik (2021) and J after Marusik &amp; Guseinov (2003). Scale bars: A–I = 0.2 mm (not provided for J). Abbreviations: Bu—bursa, Fo—fovea, Re—receptacle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683487" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683487/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Fig. 6G–I</figureCitation>
; for the description, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Zamani, A. &amp; Marusik, Y. M." box="[834,1131,547,573]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432" pagination="145 - 193" refId="ref6801" refString="Zamani, A. &amp; Marusik, Y. M. (2021) Revision of the spider family Zodariidae (Arachnida, Araneae) in Iran and Turkmenistan, with seventeen new species. ZooKeys, 1035, 145 - 193. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 1035.65767" type="journal article" year="2021">Zamani &amp; Marusik (2021)</bibRefCitation>
. In the original description, the vestigial PMEs were overlooked (
<bibRefCitation author="Zamani, A. &amp; Marusik, Y. M." box="[572,855,583,609]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432" pagination="145 - 193" refId="ref6801" refString="Zamani, A. &amp; Marusik, Y. M. (2021) Revision of the spider family Zodariidae (Arachnida, Araneae) in Iran and Turkmenistan, with seventeen new species. ZooKeys, 1035, 145 - 193. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 1035.65767" type="journal article" year="2021">Zamani &amp; Marusik 2021</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 26D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="432" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,618,644]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Comments.</emphasis>
Although the male specimen described here was collected along with the 
<typeStatus box="[1202,1300,619,645]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">holotype</typeStatus>
female, for some reason it was deposited in a separate vial and located only after the species was described.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1199,690,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,717]" box="[199,1199,690,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,690,716]" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from two localities in 
<collectingRegion box="[753,980,691,717]" country="Iran" name="Khuzestan" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Khuzestan Province</collectingRegion>
, southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[1146,1195,691,717]" name="Iran" pageId="9" pageNumber="432">Iran</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
